1341	1125	Decoding Jordan Brand’s Coldest Winter Fits	decoding-jordan-brand-s-coldest-winter-fits	published	2025-12-12 16:15:23+00	3	17	\N	With an influx of new trends infiltrating our social media feeds every day, Jordan brand is on hand to make the process of compiling your winter wardrobe that bit easier. Under its new manifesto, “...	Decoding Jordan Brand’s Coldest Winter Fits	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F09%2Fjordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-0.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><div>With an influx of new trends infiltrating our social media feeds every day, Jordan brand is on hand to make the process of compiling your winter wardrobe that bit easier. Under its new manifesto, “Coldest in the Game,” it launches a range of footwear as well as two new collections complete with all the pieces that boldly beat the chill. From the ski-inspired Mountainside range to the camo-enriched Realtree collection, the latest offerings come together to deliver two contemporary winter aesthetics, which now go head-to-head in a new Hypebeast-produced campaign. Rethinking what “cold” means today, we team up with London-based trailblazing stylist and creative consultant James Loach who puts his interpretation on the collections and accompanying Air Jordan footwear.“These style profiles clearly speak to people, and not just out of purpose,” shares Loach. As Hypebeast catches up with the stylist following the shoot, he explains how the two collections are more than fleeting trends but instead, run deep in two core communities. “For a culture that's championing streetwear, camo is such an integral part of the wardrobe - whether it’s snow camo or digi camo,” he adds. “For me, Realtree camo is the original. It’s always been there, but I love how people are now putting respect on the history of realtree itself.”The Mountainside collection, alternatively, leans towards a more sporty and technical look, aligning more with the gorp-core trend that rose in popularity after the pandemic, becoming a staple for its technical features that can take on any condition. “Beyond the mountainside, there’s a gorp-core community in cities that are styling GORE-TEX and these outerwear pieces with less harsh accessories like shirts,” says Loach. “This collection gives you an experimental platform where you can do this.”As well as tapping into these two profiles, the stylist harnesses his background growing up in London, as well as travelling to new places, where he’s met people who proudly count themselves as part of the Jordan brand community. “I like being able to pick from other inspirations like my friends. They have that same eye for style that I do,” he shares. “My approach was to just rinse all that knowledge, passion and stylistic goodness into one story.”The final looks featured in the campaign result in a uniquely structural form, achieved by clever layering and color play. “I wanted to emphasize that real chill of winter,” reflects the stylist. “I intentionally paired different fabrics together, such as nylons, wools, fleeces, cashmeres, and cottons. It’s about having those counterparts working together in different ways, each providing different purposes; whether it’s shape, texture, or purely for color – having another piece of clothing highlighted off the reflection of it.”Complementing the curated styles, the newly released Air Jordan 1 Element Low serves as the functional yet versatile base with its wraparound tread spike that Loach calls, “a striking blend of two DNAs.” He goes on to say, “The tread spike wrap is more noticeable on the blue, but the black acts like a stealthy piece of kit on icy streets and snowy terrain. That’s what makes it a staple.”So how exactly do you apply this styling blueprint to be the Coldest in the Game? The simple answer: “If you like it, own it,” exclaims Loach. “I've learnt you should never be afraid to try. If you want a really cold wardrobe, then spend the time, study the references, and understand what you love or what you don't. Ultimately, you’re only going to be left with a 10/10 outfit.”Discover the full campaign lookbook produced by Hypebeast in the gallery above. You can now shop the Mountainside and Realtree collections on Jordan brand’s website now.</div><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/2025/12/jordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info" title="Decoding Jordan Brand’s Coldest Winter Fits" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to view full gallery at Hypebeast</a></p>	\N	2025-12-13 13:07:06.348+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.348+00	published	2025-12-13 13:07:06.351+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.351+00	t	\N	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F09%2Fjordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-0.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><p>With an influx of new trends infiltrating our social media feeds every day, <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/jordan-brand">Jordan brand</a> is on hand to make the process of compiling your winter wardrobe that bit easier. Under its new manifesto, “Coldest in the Game,” it launches a range of footwear as well as two new collections complete with all the pieces that boldly beat the chill. </p><p>From the ski-inspired Mountainside range to the camo-enriched Realtree collection, the latest offerings come together to deliver two contemporary winter aesthetics, which now go head-to-head in a new Hypebeast-produced campaign. Rethinking what “cold” means today, we team up with London-based trailblazing stylist and creative consultant <a href="https://www.instagram.com/jamesloachco/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">James Loach</a> who puts his interpretation on the collections and accompanying <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/air-jordan">Air Jordan</a> footwear.</p><p>“These style profiles clearly speak to people, and not just out of purpose,” shares Loach. As Hypebeast catches up with the stylist following the shoot, he explains how the two collections are more than fleeting trends but instead, run deep in two core communities. “For a culture that's championing streetwear, camo is such an integral part of the wardrobe - whether it’s snow camo or digi camo,” he adds. “For me, Realtree camo is the original. It’s always been there, but I love how people are now putting respect on the history of realtree itself.”</p><p>The Mountainside collection, alternatively, leans towards a more sporty and technical look, aligning more with the gorp-core trend that rose in popularity after the pandemic, becoming a staple for its technical features that can take on any condition. “Beyond the mountainside, there’s a gorp-core community in cities that are styling GORE-TEX and these outerwear pieces with less harsh accessories like shirts,” says Loach. “This collection gives you an experimental platform where you can do this.”</p><p><img src="https://hypebeast.com/image/2025/12/09/jordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-1.jpg" alt="james loach jordan brand coldest in the game collections realtree mountainside outerwear camo styling winter clothing technical gorpcore " /><br /><img class="portrait" src="https://hypebeast.com/image/2025/12/09/jordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-2.jpg" alt="james loach jordan brand coldest in the game collections realtree mountainside outerwear camo styling winter clothing technical gorpcore " /><br /><img src="https://hypebeast.com/image/2025/12/09/jordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-13.jpg" alt="james loach jordan brand coldest in the game collections realtree mountainside outerwear camo styling winter clothing technical gorpcore " /></p><p>As well as tapping into these two profiles, the stylist harnesses his background growing up in London, as well as travelling to new places, where he’s met people who proudly count themselves as part of the Jordan brand community. “I like being able to pick from other inspirations like my friends. They have that same eye for style that I do,” he shares. “My approach was to just rinse all that knowledge, passion and stylistic goodness into one story.”</p><p>The final looks featured in the campaign result in a uniquely structural form, achieved by clever layering and color play. “I wanted to emphasize that real chill of winter,” reflects the stylist. “I intentionally paired different fabrics together, such as nylons, wools, fleeces, cashmeres, and cottons. It’s about having those counterparts working together in different ways, each providing different purposes; whether it’s shape, texture, or purely for color – having another piece of clothing highlighted off the reflection of it.”</p><p>Complementing the curated styles, the newly released <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/air-jordan-1-element">Air Jordan 1 Element</a> Low serves as the functional yet versatile base with its wraparound tread spike that Loach calls, “a striking blend of two DNAs.” He goes on to say, “The tread spike wrap is more noticeable on the blue, but the black acts like a stealthy piece of kit on icy streets and snowy terrain. That’s what makes it a staple.”</p><p>So how exactly do you apply this styling blueprint to be the Coldest in the Game? The simple answer: “If you like it, own it,” exclaims Loach. “I've learnt you should never be afraid to try. If you want a really cold wardrobe, then spend the time, study the references, and understand what you love or what you don't. Ultimately, you’re only going to be left with a 10/10 outfit.”</p><p>Discover the full campaign lookbook produced by Hypebeast in the gallery above. </p><p>You can now shop the Mountainside and Realtree collections on Jordan brand’s <a href="https://www.nike.com/w/coldest-in-the-game-4l26y" rel="noopener" target="_blank">website</a> now. </p><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/2025/12/jordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info" title="Decoding Jordan Brand’s Coldest Winter Fits" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to view full gallery at Hypebeast</a></p><p>    <a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/1015938/Hypebeast_RSS_300x250_Rectangle&sz=300x250&c=83373" target="_blank" rel="noopener">        <img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/1015938/Hypebeast_RSS_300x250_Rectangle&sz=300x250&c=83373" />    </a></p>	https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F09%2Fjordan-brand-hypebeast-campaign-realtree-mountainside-collection-release-info-0.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max	0	f	f	f
1342	1126	MM6 Maison Margiela’s Pre-Spring 2026 Collection Is a Study on Quietly Radical Silhouettes	mm6-maison-margiela-s-pre-spring-2026-collection-is-a-study-on-quietly-radical-silhouettes	published	2025-12-12 10:49:48+00	3	17	\N	SummaryMM6 Maison Margiela Pre-Fall 2026 explores deconstruction and dualityInspiration is drawn from school uniforms and workwear, translated with inverted structuresKey pieces include inverted wo...	MM6 Maison Margiela’s Pre-Spring 2026 Collection Is a Study on Quietly Radical Silhouettes	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F12%2Fmm6-maison-margiela-pre-fall-2026-collection-lookbook-info-000.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><div>SummaryMM6 Maison Margiela Pre-Fall 2026 explores deconstruction and dualityInspiration is drawn from school uniforms and workwear, translated with inverted structuresKey pieces include inverted workwear jackets and asymmetrical knitwearThe MM6 Maison Margiela Pre-Fall 2026 collection is built around the theme of deconstruction and duality, interpreting the classic Margiela codes through the lens of everyday, functional clothing. The collection continues the label’s signature approach of quiet subversion, presenting garments that appear straightforward at first glance but reveal engineered distortions upon closer inspection.The primary inspiration for the season is a conceptual fusion of school uniforms and workwear, translating their rigidity and utilitarianism into unexpected structures. The range maintains a familiar ease, favoring neutral and muted colors, but destabilizes traditional silhouettes with subversive treatments, such as garments that appear to be worn backward or inside out, a signature gesture of the house.Key pieces in the collection demonstrate this interplay between the ordinary and the avant-garde. A strong focus is placed on reimagining tailoring through deconstruction, notably seen in jackets and coats featuring unexpected slits or openings that alter the wearer's proportions. One standout item is the inverted workwear jacket, which features a large collar and pocketing details that appear to have been flipped to the exterior.The collection also features asymmetrical knitwear and shirting that appear half-tucked or hastily buttoned, maintaining the illusion of effortless disorder. Layering is key, with pieces like elongated jersey shirts, layered hoodies and raw-hemmed denim anchoring the more conceptual outerwear.</div><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/2025/12/mm6-maison-margiela-pre-fall-2026-collection-lookbook-info" title="MM6 Maison Margiela’s Pre-Spring 2026 Collection Is a Study on Quietly Radical Silhouettes" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to view full gallery at Hypebeast</a></p>	\N	2025-12-13 13:07:06.362+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.362+00	published	2025-12-13 13:07:06.364+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.364+00	t	\N	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F12%2Fmm6-maison-margiela-pre-fall-2026-collection-lookbook-info-000.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><p><strong>Summary</strong></p><ul><li>MM6 Maison Margiela Pre-Fall 2026 explores deconstruction and duality</li><li>Inspiration is drawn from school uniforms and workwear, translated with inverted structures</li><li>Key pieces include inverted workwear jackets and asymmetrical knitwear</li></ul><p>The <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/mm6-maison-margiela" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MM6 Maison Margiela</a> <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/pre-spring-2026" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Pre-Fall 2026</a> collection is built around the theme of deconstruction and duality, interpreting the classic Margiela codes through the lens of everyday, functional clothing. The collection continues the label’s signature approach of quiet subversion, presenting garments that appear straightforward at first glance but reveal engineered distortions upon closer inspection.</p><p>The primary inspiration for the season is a conceptual fusion of school uniforms and workwear, translating their rigidity and utilitarianism into unexpected structures. The range maintains a familiar ease, favoring neutral and muted colors, but destabilizes traditional silhouettes with subversive treatments, such as garments that appear to be worn backward or inside out, a signature gesture of the house.</p><p>Key pieces in the collection demonstrate this interplay between the ordinary and the avant-garde. A strong focus is placed on reimagining tailoring through deconstruction, notably seen in jackets and coats featuring unexpected slits or openings that alter the wearer's proportions. One standout item is the inverted workwear jacket, which features a large collar and pocketing details that appear to have been flipped to the exterior.</p><p>The collection also features asymmetrical knitwear and shirting that appear half-tucked or hastily buttoned, maintaining the illusion of effortless disorder. Layering is key, with pieces like elongated jersey shirts, layered hoodies and raw-hemmed denim anchoring the more conceptual outerwear.</p><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/2025/12/mm6-maison-margiela-pre-fall-2026-collection-lookbook-info" title="MM6 Maison Margiela’s Pre-Spring 2026 Collection Is a Study on Quietly Radical Silhouettes" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to view full gallery at Hypebeast</a></p><p>    <a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/1015938/Hypebeast_RSS_300x250_Rectangle&sz=300x250&c=99171" target="_blank" rel="noopener">        <img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/1015938/Hypebeast_RSS_300x250_Rectangle&sz=300x250&c=99171" />    </a></p>	https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F12%2Fmm6-maison-margiela-pre-fall-2026-collection-lookbook-info-000.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max	0	f	f	f
1343	1127	Denim Tears Launches Standalone Denim Label	denim-tears-launches-standalone-denim-label	published	2025-12-12 09:19:14+00	3	17	\N	SummaryDenim Tears launches its standalone denim label, DENIM BY DENIM TEARS, marking a new phase of creative independenceThe debut collection revives the Cotton Wreath motif across Straight and Lo...	Denim Tears Launches Standalone Denim Label	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F12%2Ftremaine-emory-denim-tears-by-denim-tears-brand-launch-release-info-0.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><div>SummaryDenim Tears launches its standalone denim label, DENIM BY DENIM TEARS, marking a new phase of creative independenceThe debut collection revives the Cotton Wreath motif across Straight and Loose silhouettes in multiple washesDenim Tears, the brand founded by Tremaine Emory, has announced the launch of its dedicated denim label, DENIM BY DENIM TEARS. After years of expressing its ideas through Levi’s, denim has become a direct symbol of the label’s evolution and creative autonomy. This inaugural release establishes the category’s intent clearly: denim that is unmistakably Denim Tears, rooted in the brand’s cultural storytelling and material sensibility.The inaugural collection prominently revisits the brand's iconic "Cotton Wreath" motif, first seen in their highly successful collaboration with Levi's, now applying it to a broader range of styles and washes. The initial offering includes two key silhouettes: the D-TEARS Signature Straight Leg Jean and the D-TEARS Loose Fit Jean. These are available in various washes, including vintage indigo, bleached indigo, and black. Key details include custom-designed rivets, new hardware featuring the Cotton Wreath logo, and unique stitching patterns that nod to historical garments.The DENIM BY DENIM TEARS brand is launching exclusively via the Denim Tears webstore today, with prices. The initial collection is priced between $250 - $450 USD, with subsequent drops down the pipeline. View this post on InstagramA post shared by Denim Tears (@denimtears)</div><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/2025/12/tremaine-emory-denim-tears-by-denim-tears-brand-launch-release-info" title="Denim Tears Launches Standalone Denim Label" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click here to view full gallery at Hypebeast</a></p>	\N	2025-12-13 13:07:06.376+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.375+00	published	2025-12-13 13:07:06.378+00	2025-12-13 13:07:06.378+00	t	\N	<p><img width="620" src="https://image-cdn.hypb.st/https%3A%2F%2Fhypebeast.com%2Fimage%2F2025%2F12%2F12%2Ftremaine-emory-denim-tears-by-denim-tears-brand-launch-release-info-0.jpg?w=800&cbr=1&q=90&fit=max" /></p><p><strong>Summary</strong></p><ul><li>Denim Tears launches its standalone denim label, DENIM BY DENIM TEARS, marking a new phase of creative independence</li><li>The debut collection revives the Cotton Wreath motif across Straight and Loose silhouettes in multiple washes</li></ul><p><a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/denim-tears" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Denim Tears</a>, the brand founded by <a href="https://hypebeast.com/tags/tremaine-emory" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tremaine Emory</a>, has announced the launch of its dedicated denim label, DENIM BY DENIM TEARS. After years of expressing its ideas through Levi’s, denim has become a direct symbol of the label’s evolution and creative autonomy. This inaugural release establishes the category’s intent clearly: denim that is unmistakably Denim Tears, rooted in the brand’s cultural storytelling and material sensibility.</p><p>The inaugural collection prominently revisits the brand's iconic "Cotton Wreath" motif, first seen in their highly successful collaboration with Levi's, now applying it to a broader range of styles and washes. The initial offering includes two key silhouettes: the D-TEARS Signature Straight Leg Jean and the D-TEARS Loose Fit Jean. These are available in various washes, including vintage indigo, bleached indigo, and black. Key details include custom-designed rivets, new hardware featuring the Cotton Wreath logo, and unique stitching patterns that nod to historical garments.</p><p>The DENIM BY DENIM TEARS brand is launching exclusively via the Denim Tears <a href="https://denimtears.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">webstore</a> today, with prices. The initial collection is priced between $250 - $450 USD, with subsequent drops down the pipeline.</p><p><center><br /><blockquote class="instagram-media bypass" data-instgrm-captioned data-instgrm-permalink="https://www.instagram.com/p/DSIQ9lhEYck/?utm_source=ig_embed&amp;utm_campaign=loading" data-instgrm-version="14" style=" background:#FFF; border:0; border-radius:3px; box-shadow:0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width:540px; min-width:326px; padding:0; width:99.375%; width:-webkit-calc(100% - 2px); width:calc(100% - 2px);"><div style="padding:16px;"> <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DSIQ9lhEYck/?utm_source=ig_embed&amp;utm_campaign=loading" style=" background:#FFFFFF; line-height:0; padding:0 0; text-align:center; text-decoration:none; width:100%;" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><div style=" display: flex; flex-direction: row; align-items: center;"><div style="background-color: #F4F4F4; border-radius: 50%; flex-grow: 0; height: 40px; margin-right: 14px; width: 40px;"></div><div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; flex-grow: 1; justify-content: center;"><div style=" background-color: #F4F4F4; border-radius: 4px; flex-grow: 0; height: 14px; margin-bottom: 6px; width: 100px;"></div><div style=" background-color: #F4F4F4; border-radius: 4px; flex-grow: 0; height: 14px; width: 60px;"></div></div></div><div style="padding: 19% 0;"></div><div style="display:block; height:50px; margin:0 auto 12px; width:50px;"><svg width="50px" height="50px" viewBox="0 0 60 60" version="1.1" xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="https://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><